Contributing
============

Keep changes small.  Each commit must do one thing.


SOURCE STYLE
------------

Every source file starts with an SPDX line:

        /* SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-2.0 */

Assembly source files use the syntax accepted by the BPF assembler.  For LLVM
and modern binutils this looks like:

        r0 = 0
        exit

Do not add banner comments.  Do not describe obvious instructions.  Add a
comment only when it records a verifier constraint, ABI rule, or kernel rule
that is not obvious from the instruction stream.

Keep labels local unless the loader needs the symbol.  Keep section names
explicit and stable.


COMMITS
-------

Use this subject form:

        area: change summary

Examples:

        bpf: add syscall entry tracepoint program
        build: add BPF assembler rules
        docs: describe BPF binutils requirement

The subject is lowercase after the area, imperative where possible, and no
longer than 75 columns.

The body explains why the change is needed.  Mention verifier limits, ABI
requirements, loader-visible behavior, and compatibility constraints when they
matter.  Do not repeat the diff.

End with trailers when appropriate:

        Signed-off-by: Name <mail@example.com>


ATOMIC CHANGES
--------------

A commit that adds one program does not also reformat unrelated files.  A
commit that changes build rules does not also change tracing behavior.  A
commit that fixes a verifier problem describes the failing condition and the
instruction-level fix.
